    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-13T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-13T08:00:00-05:00" n="737"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d737">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/10881: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vichy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-13T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 13, 1941—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>543. Embassy’s telegram No. 526, May 9, noon. The Embassy learned in strict
                    confidence this morning from an official source that German planes for the past
                    3 days have been arriving at Damascus and Palmyra on the way to Iraq; that 14
                    have arrived at Palmyra and <pb facs="0711" n="703" xml:id="pg_703"/> that they
                    are being permitted to refuel and take off again. We are told that General Dentz
                    requested that they land in the future at Palmyra and not at Damascus “where
                    they would be seen by too many people.” The orders permitting them to utilize
                    Syrian air fields our informant said were issued from Vichy presumably by
                    General Huntziger.<note n="65" xml:id="d737fn65">Gen. Charles Huntziger, French
                        Minister for National Defense.</note> He also said that a certain amount of
                    war material is being shipped from French supplies in Syria to Iraq under
                    instructions from Vichy though he did not know the nature of the material nor
                    quantities involved.</p>
                <p>The foregoing seems to check with Engert’s telegram 139, May 12, 4 p.m., which
                    has just arrived.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Beirut.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Leahy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
